{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17586035","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17586035"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T08:24:22+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T08:24:22+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15051"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15051","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15051"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.77,0.03,0.07,0.03,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7739"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67572"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7739","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7739"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15051"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53024"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"8115"},{"type":"tags","id":"8485"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18898"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18902"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67572","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/67572"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAcute tubular necrosis is a common cause of acute kidney injury, particularly following periods of renal ischaemia. The condition shows characteristic histological changes that progress over time.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the earliest histological change seen in acute tubular necrosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Loss of proximal tubular brush border","Complete tubular cell necrosis","Rupture of tubular basement membrane","Interstitial fibrosis","Glomerular basement membrane thickening"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn acute tubular necrosis (ATN), the \u003Cstrong\u003Eloss of proximal tubular brush border\u003C/strong\u003E is the earliest histological change observed. This occurs before other structural changes develop.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EComplete tubular cell necrosis\u003C/strong\u003E is actually relatively uncommon and occurs in a patchy distribution when present\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERupture of tubular basement membrane\u003C/strong\u003E does not typically occur - the basement membrane remains intact which allows for tubular regeneration\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInterstitial fibrosis\u003C/strong\u003E is a feature of chronic kidney disease rather than acute tubular injury\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGlomerular basement membrane thickening\u003C/strong\u003E is not a feature of ATN and is more commonly associated with conditions like diabetic nephropathy\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFollowing the initial brush border loss, other changes develop including tubular cell flattening and sloughing of cellular debris into the tubular lumen. The intact basement membrane is crucial for subsequent regeneration and recovery.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Loss of proximal tubular brush border is the earliest histological change in acute tubular necrosis","The tubular basement membrane remains intact in acute tubular necrosis, allowing regeneration","Complete tubular cell necrosis is relatively uncommon and patchy in acute tubular necrosis"],"references":["Wen Y, Yang C, Menez SP, Rosenberg AZ, Parikh CR. A Systematic Review of Clinical Characteristics and Histologic Descriptions of Acute Tubular Injury. Kidney Int Rep. 2020 Aug 31;5(11):1993-2001. doi: 10.1016/j.ekir.2020.08.026. PMID: 33163720; PMCID: PMC7609907.","Jennette, J. C., \u0026 D\u0027Agati, V. D. (2023). Heptinstall\u0027s Pathology of the Kidney. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science","Koeppen, B. M., \u0026 Stanton, B. A. (2018). Renal Physiology E-Book: Renal Physiology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53024"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15051"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53024","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/53024"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-05T19:20:24+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-05T19:22:04+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7739"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67572"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":nu